        The message arrives on a morning that starts like any other.

        I'm helping Scout clear debris from the exterior drainage system—one of those routine maintenance tasks that's become weirdly satisfying—when Holloway appears in the doorway.

        Not the usual Holloway presence—this is different, alert, vibrating with something.

        Holloway says, "It's here."

        I ask, "What's here?"

        Holloway says, "Elder Heartwood's response—the messenger from Territory Three just arrived."

        Oh—Scout bounces excitedly; they understand what this means—the answer we've been waiting for, *THE* answer.

        Holloway says, "Gather everyone—this should be received properly."

        Properly means ceremonially—within an hour every plant who's been helping me is assembled in the common area: Holloway at the center, Florence and Elder Twist positioned prominently, Remedy's mycelial network spreading across one wall, Runner coiled attentively, Velvet gathered in a thick carpet, Scout bouncing with barely-contained excitement.

        Even plants I haven't seen in weeks have shown up—this is an *EVENT.*

        Holloway indicates a spot in the center and says, "Kira, please sit here. The question was presented on your behalf. You should be central to receiving the response."

        I sit; Scout settles beside me, trembling slightly with anticipation.

        The messenger—a traveling plant I don't recognize, all wrapped leaves and patient demeanor—is given a place of honor. They've carried Elder Heartwood's wisdom across three territories; that means something.

        Holloway says, "We thank you for bringing Elder Heartwood's understanding to us—your service to the network is recognized and valued."

        The messenger inclines slightly.

        The messenger says, "It is an honor to carry such wisdom—may it serve your need."

        The room feels charged—hopeful. Everyone here believes this response will change everything.

        ¶

        Holloway says, "Please. Share Elder Heartwood's wisdom."

        The messenger settles more firmly, preparing. When the messenger begins, I realize the response isn't direct—it's layered, metaphorical, the kind of wisdom that will need interpretation.

        The messenger intones, "Elder Heartwood considered your question for four weeks and seven days—the roots stretched deep—connections formed across the network—patterns were examined from many seasons. This is the understanding that emerged."

        Four weeks—over a month of ancient consideration—that has to mean something comprehensive, right?

        The messenger continues, "Elder Heartwood speaks of the Great Adaptation—when the visitor first came, the balance shifted—what had been stable for uncounted seasons required new patterns. The ecosystem learned: some growth accelerates, some slows—equilibrium finds new expressions across time."

        I glance at Holloway; they're listening intently, absorbing every word.
      </text>
