        Runner asks sharply, "For what questions? Territory disputes? Resource allocation? Mineral depletion?"

        Vines gesture toward me, "Those are plant problems with plant timescales — this is about keeping someone alive *NOW*. Someone who doesn't have centuries to integrate gradually."

        The messenger has no answer to that.

        Scout presses against my leg—comfort, solidarity; they're upset, but their first instinct is still to check on me.

        Velvet says simply, "So that's it."

        Remedy corrects bitterly, "No *USEFUL* answer."

        Florence is very still. After a long moment, she speaks, "We placed our hope in Elder Heartwood's perspective. We believed ancient wisdom would see connections we couldn't. And the wisdom is there—vast, deep, rooted in millennia of observation."

        ¶

        Florence continues, "But it's not wisdom that helps *NOW*. It's not wisdom that cares about individuals, only patterns — not wisdom that sees Kira, only 'temporary disruption.'"

        The plants are struggling—I can see it: the hope they built up crumbling, the confidence draining away.

        Holloway finally moves, their arrangement shifting to something more determined, "Thank you for bringing the response — we understand it wasn't what we needed, but you fulfilled your service honorably."

        The messenger bows slightly and retreats—probably glad to escape the heavy disappointment filling the room.

        After they leave, nobody speaks for a while.

        This was supposed to be the moment everything made sense—the comprehensive framework arriving to explain how cross-species care works, how to bridge incompatible needs, how to actually help me survive.

        Instead, the answer was, "Wait patiently for the 'temporary problem' to die."

        I say into the silence, "Well — I guess we're on our own."

        It comes out more bitter than I intended, but also… kind of true?

        The plants look at me — Holloway, Florence, Remedy, Runner, Velvet, Scout — all the beings who've been trying so hard to help me, counting on someone wiser to tell them how.

        And that someone either didn't understand the question, didn't care about the answer, or operates on timescales where my entire lifespan is barely worth noticing.

        We're on our own.

        That should be terrifying — maybe it is. But mostly, right now, I just feel tired.
